WEBVTT

1
00:02:48.757 --> 00:02:50.382
<i>Yes, ma'am.</i>
<i>How are you doing this afternoon?</i>

2
00:02:50.421 --> 00:02:52.203
<i>Now, is this Rose Hill?</i>

3
00:02:52.403 --> 00:02:54.414
<i>Good.
This is Ed Couch.</i>

4
00:02:54.469 --> 00:02:55.477
<i>Uh-huh.</i>

5
00:02:55.518 --> 00:02:58.273
<i>I, I'm Vesta Adcock's nephew.</i>

6
00:02:58.476 --> 00:03:01.070
<i>I need to get up there and see her,
but I'm gonna be a little bit late,</i>

7
00:03:01.101 --> 00:03:03.648
<i>because, I'll tell you what,
I'm lost out here.</i>

8
00:03:03.889 --> 00:03:07.507
<i>We are off the Alabama Interstate,
but I don't know where.</i>

9
00:03:08.030 --> 00:03:09.570
<i>Okay.</i>

10
00:03:43.367 --> 00:03:45.044
Did you hear that?

11
00:03:45.138 --> 00:03:46.458
What?

12
00:03:47.359 --> 00:03:48.958
The train.

13
00:03:49.239 --> 00:03:51.458
No, I didn't hear no train.

14
00:03:53.879 --> 00:03:56.282
Oh, nothing, I guess.

15
00:03:56.798 --> 00:03:58.790
Where's Whistle Stop on the map?

16
00:03:58.829 --> 00:04:00.290
I can't find it.

17
00:04:00.669 --> 00:04:04.587
Why did you tell me to turn right
ten miles back there, then?

18
00:04:06.660 --> 00:04:09.573
God, you've got a negative sense
of direction, honey.

19
00:04:10.238 --> 00:04:12.018
I'm sorry.

20
00:04:12.647 --> 00:04:16.729
Oh, Ed, your aunt's gonna be
so disappointed we're late.

21
00:04:17.032 --> 00:04:20.763
I know she's been looking
forward to this visit all week long.

22
00:04:21.016 --> 00:04:23.415
Bless her sweet little old heart.

23
00:04:28.731 --> 00:04:31.473
Hey, how's my sweet
Auntie V this afternoon?

24
00:04:31.513 --> 00:04:32.826
Remember us?

25
00:04:32.865 --> 00:04:34.014
Come on in.

26
00:04:34.076 --> 00:04:35.318
<i>Don't you look pretty?</i>

27
00:04:35.357 --> 00:04:38.232
<i>- We've brought you something this sweet.
- Oh, let me look at you.</i>

28
00:04:38.280 --> 00:04:39.943
<i>Honey, don't panic.</i>

29
00:04:40.015 --> 00:04:42.732
<i>Don't you know
Evelyn loves you?</i>

30
00:04:43.412 --> 00:04:44.990
Well, honey.

31
00:04:45.015 --> 00:04:48.045
I guess it'd be better if you just wait
out here for me or something.

32
00:04:48.100 --> 00:04:49.654
I'll, I'll get all this stuff.

33
00:04:49.717 --> 00:04:50.764
Well, if...

34
00:04:50.794 --> 00:04:52.560
If you think it's best.

35
00:04:52.630 --> 00:04:54.635
Yeah, I do, this time.
Okay?

36
00:04:56.274 --> 00:04:58.196
Have a nice day, Aunt Vesta.

37
00:04:58.231 --> 00:05:00.290
<i>Don't you pitch a fit like that</i>

38
00:05:12.563 --> 00:05:15.125
Did you know they took
my gall bladder out?

39
00:05:16.008 --> 00:05:17.938
Uh, no, I didn't.

40
00:05:18.289 --> 00:05:19.860
Oh, yes.

41
00:05:20.047 --> 00:05:23.071
Still in the hospital in a jar.

42
00:05:23.799 --> 00:05:26.305
I guess that's where they keep them.

43
00:05:26.868 --> 00:05:28.518
I guess.

44
00:05:29.104 --> 00:05:31.291
When I was in the hospital,

45
00:05:31.401 --> 00:05:35.831
the nurse gave me one of them
Fleet enemas they're so fond of.

46
00:05:36.448 --> 00:05:38.182
Mrs. Cleo Threadgoode.

47
00:05:38.237 --> 00:05:40.784
82-year-old widow.
Imagine that.

48
00:05:41.526 --> 00:05:44.424
Actually, everybody calls me Ninny.

49
00:05:44.643 --> 00:05:47.534
Of course, I'm just visiting here.

50
00:05:48.026 --> 00:05:51.174
Did you ever have
one of them Fleet enemas?

51
00:05:52.291 --> 00:05:53.424
Um...

52
00:05:53.460 --> 00:05:54.823
Well...

53
00:05:55.518 --> 00:05:56.713
No.

54
00:05:56.849 --> 00:05:58.823
You'd remember it.

55
00:05:59.846 --> 00:06:03.190
Me and my friend, Mrs. Otis,
come from Whistle Stop.

56
00:06:03.418 --> 00:06:05.926
You ever been to Whistle Stop?

57
00:06:06.020 --> 00:06:09.004
Why, yes.
I just passed by there today.

58
00:06:09.082 --> 00:06:13.147
She's lived down the street from me
for, oh, 30 years or more.

59
00:06:13.639 --> 00:06:15.943
After her son died,...

60
00:06:16.082 --> 00:06:19.748
her daughter-in-law had a fit for her
to come live here at the nursing home,

61
00:06:19.779 --> 00:06:22.404
and they asked me to come with her
and be her roommate.

62
00:06:22.467 --> 00:06:24.037
Mrs. Otis don't know it,

63
00:06:24.068 --> 00:06:28.459
but I'm going back home
just as soon as she gets settled in good.

64
00:06:29.873 --> 00:06:33.029
Does the name "Idgie Threadgoode"
ring a bell?

65
00:06:33.162 --> 00:06:34.584
Um...

66
00:06:34.670 --> 00:06:36.928
No, ma'am.
I don't think so.

67
00:06:36.967 --> 00:06:39.217
You'd remember her.

68
00:06:39.803 --> 00:06:43.545
You see, I was practically adopted
by the Threadgoode family.

69
00:06:43.584 --> 00:06:45.842
- I married her brother, Cleo.
- Oh. Uh-huh.

70
00:06:45.907 --> 00:06:47.095
Yeah.

71
00:06:47.125 --> 00:06:50.729
Idgie and her friend, Ruth,
ran the Whistle Stop Café.

72
00:06:50.775 --> 00:06:52.158
Oh.

73
00:06:52.893 --> 00:06:56.463
Idgie was a character, all right.

74
00:06:56.836 --> 00:07:03.351
But, how anybody could have thought
she murdered that man is beyond me.

75
00:07:04.070 --> 00:07:05.562
I beg your pardon?

76
00:07:05.601 --> 00:07:08.836
Well, you sit and relax awhile.
I'll tell you all about it.

77
00:07:08.965 --> 00:07:11.140
Oh, now, let's see um...

78
00:07:11.657 --> 00:07:15.626
I remember the day they pulled
that truck up out of the river.

79
00:07:15.915 --> 00:07:19.103
<i>That same rainy summer day,</i>

80
00:07:19.189 --> 00:07:21.462
<i>Idgie Threadgoode was arrested</i>

81
00:07:21.525 --> 00:07:24.095
<i>for the murder
of the owner of that truck,</i>

82
00:07:24.299 --> 00:07:26.111
<i>Frank Bennett.</i>

83
00:07:29.599 --> 00:07:31.833
I guess to understand Idgie,

84
00:07:31.857 --> 00:07:36.013
you'd have to start way back
with her brother, Buddy.

85
00:07:37.067 --> 00:07:41.606
<i>Idgie was Buddy's pet
from the day she was born.</i>

86
00:07:43.003 --> 00:07:46.673
<i>I remember the day we was all
getting ready for Leona's wedding.</i>

87
00:07:46.860 --> 00:07:48.657
<i>The war had just ended.</i>

88
00:07:48.719 --> 00:07:50.813
<i>The, the "Great" one, you know.</i>

89
00:07:51.399 --> 00:07:54.917
<i>And another one was about
to begin in the Threadgoode house.</i>

90
00:07:56.165 --> 00:07:59.087
<i>Sipsey, honey, is that finished?</i>

91
00:07:59.112 --> 00:08:00.165
<i>What you doing?</i>

92
00:08:00.196 --> 00:08:02.190
Oh, Buddy.
Buddy, get dressed, honey.

93
00:08:02.229 --> 00:08:04.643
<i>- Mama?</i>
- Leona, what is it?

94
00:08:04.745 --> 00:08:05.977
Idgie's upstairs in her room,

95
00:08:06.025 --> 00:08:08.610
and she, she said she won't come out
just as long as she lives.

96
00:08:08.641 --> 00:08:10.993
- Mama, she is gonna ruin my wedding.
- Shh.

97
00:08:11.024 --> 00:08:13.964
Why, Leona, you're gonna be
the most beautiful bride, you hear?

98
00:08:13.995 --> 00:08:16.987
Well, of course she is, Papa.

99
00:08:17.604 --> 00:08:20.073
Your papa has spent
every last nickel he has

100
00:08:20.112 --> 00:08:21.519
just to make you happy.

101
00:08:21.557 --> 00:08:24.792
Now, you try to act
a little grateful, young lady.

102
00:08:25.447 --> 00:08:27.846
Imogen Louise Threadgoode!

103
00:08:28.654 --> 00:08:30.609
This is your mama!

104
00:08:33.562 --> 00:08:35.429
You come down here...

105
00:08:35.508 --> 00:08:36.719
right now.

106
00:08:36.764 --> 00:08:38.462
Do you hear me?

107
00:08:38.509 --> 00:08:40.205
Buddy, you go fetch her.
She'll listen to you.

108
00:08:40.244 --> 00:08:41.299
Come on down, Little Bit.

109
00:08:41.340 --> 00:08:43.423
There's no firing squad waiting for you.

110
00:08:43.482 --> 00:08:45.166
Ohh.

111
00:08:45.214 --> 00:08:46.712
Come on, honey.

112
00:08:46.760 --> 00:08:49.034
Now, let us see you.

113
00:08:49.706 --> 00:08:51.737
Oh, you look so pretty.

114
00:08:51.796 --> 00:08:54.995
- I see London, I see...
<i>- Hush!</i>

115
00:08:56.266 --> 00:08:58.229
Julian, hush.

116
00:08:59.526 --> 00:09:01.409
Come ahead, sweetheart.

117
00:09:03.073 --> 00:09:05.705
<i>You look awful nice in that.</i>

118
00:09:05.847 --> 00:09:07.009
Mama!

119
00:09:07.034 --> 00:09:08.385
You look fine, Idgie.

120
00:09:08.424 --> 00:09:10.760
- She looks like a monkey.
- Julian.

121
00:09:10.815 --> 00:09:12.440
Stop it right this second.

122
00:09:12.487 --> 00:09:13.963
- Take it back!
- Idgie!

123
00:09:14.034 --> 00:09:15.917
- Take it back.
- Hey, hey, hey.

124
00:09:16.166 --> 00:09:18.527
I told you she was
gonna ruin my wedding!

125
00:09:18.560 --> 00:09:19.604
Idgie, get up.

126
00:09:19.629 --> 00:09:21.065
Take it back!

127
00:09:21.096 --> 00:09:22.432
Take it back!

128
00:09:23.338 --> 00:09:25.066
Tell him to take it back.

129
00:09:25.128 --> 00:09:27.273
- I'll get you for this.
- No, Buddy.

130
00:09:28.559 --> 00:09:31.770
<i>Julian, I am really cross with you now...</i>

131
00:09:31.855 --> 00:09:34.207
<i>You know that we have to be careful
when she's dressing up.</i>

132
00:09:34.254 --> 00:09:36.285
<i>- Pain! She's just a pain.
- You know it matters to her.</i>

133
00:09:36.340 --> 00:09:38.988
<i>- My wedding is ruining.
- Leona, will you stop shrieking, honey?</i>

134
00:09:39.192 --> 00:09:40.777
<i>This is your wedding day.</i>

135
00:09:53.275 --> 00:09:55.848
Looks like you got yourself
up a tree, Little Bit.

136
00:09:57.160 --> 00:09:59.480
I'm sick of people making fun of me.

137
00:10:00.020 --> 00:10:02.504
So you're gonna stay
up here all day long?

138
00:10:02.605 --> 00:10:03.637
Yep.

139
00:10:03.676 --> 00:10:04.957
The hell with them.

140
00:10:05.043 --> 00:10:08.246
Who wants to wear
that stupid old dress anyway?

141
00:10:09.723 --> 00:10:11.434
Did I ever tell you
about the oysters?

142
00:10:11.465 --> 00:10:12.496
Oysters?

143
00:10:12.534 --> 00:10:14.699
- Didn't I tell you about the oysters?
- No.

144
00:10:15.044 --> 00:10:16.894
<i>Think about all the millions of oysters</i>

145
00:10:16.919 --> 00:10:19.411
just lying around
on the bottom of the ocean.

146
00:10:19.622 --> 00:10:21.402
And then one day...

147
00:10:21.566 --> 00:10:24.402
God comes along and
He sees one and He says,

148
00:10:24.481 --> 00:10:27.113
"I think I'm gonna make
that one different."

149
00:10:27.409 --> 00:10:29.331
Did you know what He does?

150
00:10:29.761 --> 00:10:32.261
He puts a little piece of sand in it.

151
00:10:32.917 --> 00:10:35.792
And guess what it can do
that the others can't.

152
00:10:36.087 --> 00:10:37.323
What?

153
00:10:37.370 --> 00:10:39.995
It can make a beautiful pearl.

154
00:10:40.804 --> 00:10:43.236
What if God made a mistake?

155
00:10:44.158 --> 00:10:45.176
Well...

156
00:10:45.215 --> 00:10:46.465
the way I figure it...

157
00:10:46.496 --> 00:10:48.166
He never makes mistakes.

158
00:10:48.220 --> 00:10:50.439
I mean, He made sure
we got together.

159
00:10:50.752 --> 00:10:55.082
He made sure you got the best-looking,
most charming brother in the world,

160
00:10:55.129 --> 00:10:56.910
who's gonna beat you
to the chocolate cake.

161
00:10:56.942 --> 00:10:58.887
You will not.

162
00:11:00.009 --> 00:11:02.197
I got you out of the tree now,
didn't I?

163
00:11:02.339 --> 00:11:04.105
Did not.

164
00:11:04.314 --> 00:11:07.962
<i>Into this estate, these two people
come now to be joined.</i>

165
00:11:08.056 --> 00:11:10.265
<i>If any man present can show cause</i>

166
00:11:10.304 --> 00:11:12.812
<i>why they might not
lawfully be joined together,</i>

167
00:11:12.878 --> 00:11:16.788
let him speak now,
or forever after hold his peace.

168
00:11:17.477 --> 00:11:19.074
Please, be seated.

169
00:11:22.692 --> 00:11:24.293
If either of you know any reason

170
00:11:24.340 --> 00:11:28.535
<i>why you may not justly
be joined together in holy matrimony</i>

171
00:11:28.778 --> 00:11:30.824
do you now confess it?

172
00:11:40.692 --> 00:11:43.130
It is in your will to proceed.

173
00:11:43.497 --> 00:11:46.442
<i>Do you, Charles Osgood Justice--?</i>

174
00:11:52.397 --> 00:11:54.102
<i>Thank you.
I don't know what we'd do</i>

175
00:11:54.142 --> 00:11:56.001
<i>without your generosity
and your kindness.</i>

176
00:11:56.041 --> 00:11:57.579
<i>Sipsey, honey, especially you.</i>

177
00:11:57.610 --> 00:12:00.548
<i>- Look at what you've done.
- Oh, you're welcome, Mrs. Threadgoode.</i>

178
00:12:01.422 --> 00:12:03.550
Give me that,
you rascal, you!

179
00:12:07.816 --> 00:12:08.855
Oh!

180
00:12:08.886 --> 00:12:11.051
- Jump on my back.
<i>- I don't think that there ever was</i>

181
00:12:11.090 --> 00:12:13.347
<i>a sweeter boy than
Buddy Threadgoode.</i>

182
00:12:13.372 --> 00:12:15.215
You look beautiful today, Lily.

183
00:12:15.261 --> 00:12:17.664
Yes.
Lily, you sure do.

184
00:12:17.722 --> 00:12:20.683
<i>I had the biggest crush on him.</i>

185
00:12:21.436 --> 00:12:23.613
<i>He was a terrible ﬂirt.</i>

186
00:12:23.754 --> 00:12:27.121
<i>But, his heart belonged to Ruth Jamison.</i>

187
00:12:28.535 --> 00:12:30.972
<i>Now, she was the daughter
of a friend of his mama's</i>

188
00:12:31.002 --> 00:12:33.082
<i>who was visiting that summer.</i>

189
00:12:33.480 --> 00:12:34.957
Ruth Jamison,

190
00:12:35.004 --> 00:12:36.981
you're just the one
I've been looking for.

191
00:12:37.013 --> 00:12:38.480
Are you thirsty?

192
00:12:38.527 --> 00:12:40.730
Let's go visit someplace else.

193
00:12:46.563 --> 00:12:47.657
If you think that's a big lake,

194
00:12:47.689 --> 00:12:49.571
you should've seen the one
next to our house.

195
00:12:49.609 --> 00:12:51.501
We used to swim in it and fish.

196
00:12:51.548 --> 00:12:53.079
I sure do miss it.

197
00:12:53.125 --> 00:12:54.423
I sure do.

198
00:12:54.460 --> 00:12:55.868
Well, what happened to it?

199
00:12:55.915 --> 00:12:57.165
Did it dry up?

200
00:12:57.200 --> 00:12:58.937
No, worse than that.

201
00:12:58.976 --> 00:13:00.624
You see, last fall,
a big flock of ducks,

202
00:13:00.663 --> 00:13:04.162
about 40 or 50 of them,
landed right smack in the middle of it.

203
00:13:04.351 --> 00:13:06.601
While they were sitting in it,
this fluke thing happened.

204
00:13:06.632 --> 00:13:10.085
You see, the temperature dropped so fast
that the whole lake froze...

205
00:13:10.187 --> 00:13:11.790
in three seconds,
just like that.

206
00:13:11.837 --> 00:13:13.603
No, those poor little ducks.

207
00:13:13.634 --> 00:13:14.720
Did it kill them?

208
00:13:14.751 --> 00:13:16.157
No, they flew off...

209
00:13:16.205 --> 00:13:17.663
and took the lake with them.

210
00:13:17.725 --> 00:13:21.194
Why, to this very day,
that lake is somewhere over in Georgia.

211
00:13:22.889 --> 00:13:25.249
Buddy Threadgoode.

212
00:13:36.226 --> 00:13:37.640
Just come a little closer.

213
00:13:37.680 --> 00:13:39.406
I want to give you something.

214
00:13:39.506 --> 00:13:41.022
<i>Come here.</i>

215
00:13:45.279 --> 00:13:46.678
Whoa!

216
00:13:51.961 --> 00:13:55.337
<i>Come back here Mrs. Hat.
Where do you think you're going?</i>

217
00:13:57.798 --> 00:13:59.244
Woo-oo!

218
00:13:59.298 --> 00:14:00.673
I've got it.
Hold on, Ruth.

219
00:14:00.704 --> 00:14:02.408
Hold on, Little Bit.

220
00:14:06.649 --> 00:14:09.360
<i>It's just--
All right, I've got it.</i>

221
00:14:12.758 --> 00:14:14.196
Come here, you damn hat.

222
00:14:14.235 --> 00:14:15.618
Got it! Oh!

223
00:14:15.672 --> 00:14:17.149
<i>Oh, I meant to do that</i>

224
00:14:19.898 --> 00:14:21.846
I've got it!

225
00:14:23.093 --> 00:14:24.970
<i>Ta-da!</i>

226
00:14:26.527 --> 00:14:28.072
All right.

227
00:14:28.446 --> 00:14:29.486
Damn.

228
00:14:29.533 --> 00:14:30.814
Come on.

229
00:14:39.499 --> 00:14:41.171
Come on.
Get off.

230
00:14:41.225 --> 00:14:42.577
Get off.

231
00:14:42.755 --> 00:14:44.710
- Come on.
- Buddy!

232
00:14:45.053 --> 00:14:46.616
<i>- Buddy!</i>
- All right, don't you worry.

233
00:14:46.655 --> 00:14:48.421
<i>Buddy Threadgoode!</i>

234
00:14:50.288 --> 00:14:51.851
<i>Come on, Buddy!</i>

235
00:14:51.893 --> 00:14:53.780
<i>- Enough playing.</i>
- Get out of there.

236
00:14:55.219 --> 00:14:56.838
Get out of there.

237
00:14:57.268 --> 00:14:58.761
<i>Buddy Threadgoode!</i>

238
00:14:58.799 --> 00:15:00.252
<i>Buddy!</i>

239
00:15:02.330 --> 00:15:05.065
<i>- Come on, Buddy!
- Buddy!</i>

240
00:15:06.011 --> 00:15:07.604
Buddy!

241
00:15:08.365 --> 00:15:10.201
<i>Buddy!</i>

242
00:15:10.623 --> 00:15:12.998
No!

243
00:15:14.013 --> 00:15:16.029
<i>Buddy!</i>

244
00:15:16.248 --> 00:15:18.880
<i>Buddy, no!</i>

245
00:15:18.928 --> 00:15:20.513
<i>No!</i>

246
00:15:20.570 --> 00:15:22.279
<i>Buddy!</i>

247
00:15:22.445 --> 00:15:23.906
<i>- Let go of her.
- No!</i>

248
00:15:23.958 --> 00:15:25.703
Buddy!

249
00:15:25.805 --> 00:15:26.969
Let me go!

250
00:15:27.001 --> 00:15:28.110
No.

251
00:15:28.938 --> 00:15:30.156
<i>- What is it?</i>
- No!

252
00:15:30.211 --> 00:15:31.313
Buddy!

253
00:15:31.344 --> 00:15:32.516
- Idgie!
- Come on now.

254
00:15:32.547 --> 00:15:34.266
- We've got to get back to the house.
- Buddy!

255
00:15:34.305 --> 00:15:35.789
<i>- Do not go there.</i>
- No, Mama.

256
00:15:35.844 --> 00:15:38.305
<i>- Come on, Mama.
- Come on, we've got to go home.</i>

257
00:15:38.453 --> 00:15:39.680
Buddy!

258
00:15:39.727 --> 00:15:41.906
- Buddy!
<i>- You have to be strong. It's gonna be OK.</i>

259
00:15:41.961 --> 00:15:44.938
Buddy!

260
00:15:45.180 --> 00:15:47.953
The Lord is my shepherd,
I shall not want.

261
00:15:48.019 --> 00:15:51.047
<i>Oh, it like to have killed us all.</i>

262
00:15:52.641 --> 00:15:55.633
<i>But nary a one took it
as hard as Idgie.</i>

263
00:15:58.783 --> 00:16:02.658
<i>Everyone thought she'd die
right along with him.</i>

264
00:16:20.214 --> 00:16:21.818
<i>Night after night,</i>

265
00:16:21.865 --> 00:16:23.896
<i>she stayed by the river.</i>

266
00:16:24.847 --> 00:16:28.622
<i>Big George was the only soul
she'd let near her, and...</i>

267
00:16:28.716 --> 00:16:31.381
<i>he watched over her
night and day.</i>

268
00:16:32.506 --> 00:16:34.865
<i>You know,
a heart can be broken,</i>

269
00:16:34.904 --> 00:16:37.857
<i>but, it still keeps a-beating
just the same.</i>

270
00:16:38.046 --> 00:16:39.148
Oh, Miss Idgie.

271
00:16:39.188 --> 00:16:40.687
You'll have to keep this blanket on

272
00:16:40.727 --> 00:16:43.203
or you'll catch your death of cold,
you hear me now?

273
00:16:45.132 --> 00:16:47.304
- That's so sad.
- Uh-huh.

274
00:16:56.588 --> 00:16:58.307
Would you like one of these?

275
00:16:58.362 --> 00:16:59.393
Oh!

276
00:16:59.432 --> 00:17:00.713
Thank you, honey.

277
00:17:00.775 --> 00:17:02.292
Evelyn?

278
00:17:02.878 --> 00:17:04.885
Eve, honey,
we gotta get going.

279
00:17:04.932 --> 00:17:06.838
The Braves game's fixing to start.

280
00:17:06.886 --> 00:17:09.338
And you're gonna miss your... thing.

281
00:17:10.026 --> 00:17:11.112
Excuse me.

282
00:17:11.143 --> 00:17:13.140
That's my husband, Ed.

283
00:17:13.178 --> 00:17:14.315
Hi, ma'am.

284
00:17:14.362 --> 00:17:15.581
How you doing?

285
00:17:15.627 --> 00:17:17.081
Um...

286
00:17:18.439 --> 00:17:20.861
I can't believe Buddy died.

287
00:17:20.914 --> 00:17:22.650
Neither could I.

288
00:17:24.322 --> 00:17:25.760
Oh, well...

289
00:17:25.791 --> 00:17:27.947
I enjoyed talking to you, honey.

290
00:17:28.009 --> 00:17:29.080
What's your name?

291
00:17:29.111 --> 00:17:30.181
Um, Evelyn.

292
00:17:30.213 --> 00:17:31.869
Evelyn Couch.

293
00:17:32.056 --> 00:17:33.698
I've got to go.

294
00:17:33.744 --> 00:17:36.244
You come back and see me,
you hear?

295
00:17:37.220 --> 00:17:38.744
Okay.

296
00:17:38.815 --> 00:17:40.290
Bye-bye.

297
00:17:40.824 --> 00:17:45.774
Well, first of all, I want you
to truly dedicate yourselves

298
00:17:45.799 --> 00:17:50.004
<i>to finding little ways
to putting that magic that sparks</i>

299
00:17:50.043 --> 00:17:52.114
back into your marriage.

300
00:17:52.235 --> 00:17:55.373
When we think
of romance and marriage,

301
00:17:55.420 --> 00:17:58.553
what is the first thought
that comes into your mind?

302
00:17:58.631 --> 00:18:00.186
Divorce.

303
00:18:00.358 --> 00:18:03.930
Remember when marriage counselors used
to tell you to wrap yourself in cellophane

304
00:18:03.969 --> 00:18:06.225
to put a little charge into your marriage?

305
00:18:06.279 --> 00:18:08.381
Do we really pay for these lectures?

306
00:18:08.420 --> 00:18:11.983
<i>So you can see,
it is truly up to you...</i>

307
00:18:12.039 --> 00:18:16.297
<i>to put romance back
into your relationship.</i>

308
00:18:22.533 --> 00:18:26.449
♪ <i>Oh, yeah</i> ♪

309
00:18:28.308 --> 00:18:33.687
♪ <i>As I walk this land of broken dreams</i> ♪

310
00:18:33.757 --> 00:18:38.539
♪ <i>I have visions of many things</i> ♪

311
00:18:38.742 --> 00:18:43.025
♪ <i>- Happiness is just an illusion</i> ♪
- Hi, honey.

312
00:18:43.065 --> 00:18:44.791
Evelyn, have you gone insane?

313
00:18:44.838 --> 00:18:46.939
My God, people can see you!

314
00:18:47.275 --> 00:18:49.533
What if I'd have been
the paperboy or something, honey?

315
00:18:49.588 --> 00:18:51.541
Get, get in there.

316
00:18:51.751 --> 00:18:54.135
What are you thinking about?

317
00:18:55.398 --> 00:18:56.963
<i>Evelyn.</i>

318
00:18:58.986 --> 00:19:00.814
- Evelyn!
- Oh.

319
00:19:00.885 --> 00:19:01.947
You know?

320
00:19:02.002 --> 00:19:04.784
What we really need,
instead of this baloney,

321
00:19:04.822 --> 00:19:08.705
is an assertiveness training class
for southern women.

322
00:19:08.822 --> 00:19:12.158
But, that's a contradiction
in terms, isn't it?

323
00:19:12.541 --> 00:19:14.002
Especially you, sweetheart.

324
00:19:14.027 --> 00:19:16.127
You're living in the Dark Ages.

325
00:19:17.580 --> 00:19:22.792
♪ <i>The roots of love grow all around</i> ♪

326
00:19:22.924 --> 00:19:27.590
♪ <i>But for me they come tumbling down</i> ♪

327
00:19:27.731 --> 00:19:32.785
♪ <i>Every day heartaches grow
a little stronger</i> ♪

328
00:19:32.864 --> 00:19:38.293
♪ <i>I can't stand this pain much longer</i> ♪

329
00:19:38.960 --> 00:19:40.382
- Hi, honey.
- Hi.

330
00:19:40.421 --> 00:19:41.743
Ah, I need one of those.

331
00:19:41.782 --> 00:19:43.384
Mmm, you smell good, too.

332
00:19:43.439 --> 00:19:45.453
- Thank you.
- I need one of these.

333
00:19:46.462 --> 00:19:49.025
- Oh, this looks good.
- Uh-huh.

334
00:19:49.221 --> 00:19:50.828
Yes, indeed.

335
00:19:50.895 --> 00:19:55.958
♪ <i>Always moving but going nowhere</i> ♪

336
00:19:56.114 --> 00:19:59.489
♪ <i>- What becomes of the brokenhearted</i> ♪
<i>- He bats at the right side...</i>

337
00:19:59.755 --> 00:20:00.911
<i>Cos he's left-handed.</i>

338
00:20:00.941 --> 00:20:02.411
Ed.

339
00:20:05.325 --> 00:20:07.676
Why don't you come in
and sit down at the table

340
00:20:07.708 --> 00:20:09.161
and have dinner with me?

341
00:20:09.186 --> 00:20:11.137
I'm sorry, honey.
The game's almost over.

342
00:20:11.169 --> 00:20:12.739
I just wanted to see a bit of it.

343
00:20:12.779 --> 00:20:13.880
Why are you so dressed up?

344
00:20:13.919 --> 00:20:15.302
Honey, don't get
in the way there.

345
00:20:15.335 --> 00:20:16.841
Just scoot over just a bit.

346
00:20:21.152 --> 00:20:22.459
Ed?

347
00:20:22.648 --> 00:20:25.601
If I'd answered the door
wearing only cellophane,

348
00:20:25.749 --> 00:20:28.485
would you still be watching
the baseball game?

349
00:20:29.243 --> 00:20:32.532
No, honey, I'd probably be
checking you into a loony bin.

350
00:20:58.717 --> 00:20:59.733
<i>Hi, sugar.</i>

351
00:20:59.758 --> 00:21:01.237
<i>- How's my little dumpling?</i>
- Trick or treat?

352
00:21:01.276 --> 00:21:02.279
<i>You're gonna throw</i>

353
00:21:02.304 --> 00:21:04.012
<i>- one of them hissy fits, are you?
- Happy Halloween! Oh, no.</i>

354
00:21:04.044 --> 00:21:06.463
No, no, no, no, no, no, no, no, no!

355
00:21:06.549 --> 00:21:08.915
- Oh, Lord.
<i>- You are meaner than a damn snake.</i>

356
00:21:08.940 --> 00:21:10.809
I'm glad you're feeling better,
aunt Vesta.

357
00:21:10.853 --> 00:21:14.294
<i>- You need to get back in bed, honey.</i>
- Good thing your eyesight's failing.

358
00:21:24.784 --> 00:21:26.716
- Hey!
- Mmm. Oh.

359
00:21:27.279 --> 00:21:28.294
Hey.

360
00:21:28.334 --> 00:21:30.717
I was hoping you'd be here.

361
00:21:30.779 --> 00:21:33.232
My roommate, Mrs. Otis,
said I could stay

362
00:21:33.271 --> 00:21:34.747
and visit with her and her family,

363
00:21:34.779 --> 00:21:36.435
but I said, "Thank you kindly,

364
00:21:36.474 --> 00:21:39.138
but I think I might have
my own visitor."

365
00:21:39.177 --> 00:21:41.482
And here you are!

366
00:21:41.560 --> 00:21:42.958
Well, now, sit down.

367
00:21:43.052 --> 00:21:45.646
- Thank you.
- And doughnuts to boot.

368
00:21:46.036 --> 00:21:48.005
- You can't beat that.
- Well...

369
00:21:48.091 --> 00:21:50.638
- Help yourself, Mrs. Threadgoode.
- Oh, thank you.

370
00:21:50.690 --> 00:21:52.372
How's your friend?

371
00:21:52.504 --> 00:21:54.325
- Mrs. Otis?
- Mmm-hmm.

372
00:21:54.381 --> 00:21:56.122
Well, not so good.

373
00:21:56.154 --> 00:21:57.365
Oh.

374
00:21:57.410 --> 00:22:01.513
Looks like I won't be getting home
for quite a while, and I sure miss it.

375
00:22:03.599 --> 00:22:06.443
Funny what you miss
when you're away from home.

376
00:22:07.044 --> 00:22:09.205
I miss the smell of coffee.

377
00:22:09.257 --> 00:22:11.154
And bacon frying.

378
00:22:12.365 --> 00:22:13.756
Oh.

379
00:22:13.919 --> 00:22:16.857
What I wouldn't give for a plate
of fried green tomatoes

380
00:22:16.896 --> 00:22:19.373
like we used to have at the café.

381
00:22:19.708 --> 00:22:21.138
Ooh...

382
00:22:26.102 --> 00:22:28.961
I never told you
about the café, did I?

383
00:22:29.011 --> 00:22:30.297
No, ma'am.

384
00:22:30.352 --> 00:22:31.899
Oh, well...

385
00:22:31.973 --> 00:22:33.961
Now, let me back up a bit.

386
00:22:35.297 --> 00:22:36.759
<i>You see...</i>

387
00:22:36.910 --> 00:22:40.625
<i>Idgie never quite
got over losing Buddy.</i>

388
00:22:44.414 --> 00:22:46.625
<i>She hardly ever come home.</i>

389
00:22:46.961 --> 00:22:50.141
<i>Only Big George knew how to find her.</i>

390
00:22:50.547 --> 00:22:54.086
<i>She just didn't seem to care
about anything any more.</i>

391
00:22:54.618 --> 00:22:56.422
<i>And then one summer day...</i>

392
00:22:56.539 --> 00:22:58.485
<i>her mama sent for her.</i>

393
00:22:58.821 --> 00:23:00.165
<i>Like they say...</i>

394
00:23:00.235 --> 00:23:03.586
<i>God never shuts one door
without opening another.</i>

395
00:23:04.468 --> 00:23:05.868
<i>That was also the day</i>

396
00:23:05.899 --> 00:23:07.977
<i>- Idgie met Frank Bennett.</i>
- Mama!

397
00:23:08.176 --> 00:23:10.649
<i>The man whose murder
got her arrested.</i>

398
00:23:11.035 --> 00:23:13.000
Well, hello there, miss.

399
00:23:13.084 --> 00:23:15.000
And who might you be?

400
00:23:16.079 --> 00:23:17.493
Towanda to you.

401
00:23:17.524 --> 00:23:18.718
Who are you?

402
00:23:18.743 --> 00:23:22.633
Oh, Frank Bennett's the name,
Miss Towanda.

403
00:23:23.500 --> 00:23:26.613
I must say, you are looking
mighty fine today.

404
00:23:27.113 --> 00:23:31.194
Are you a politician, or
does lying just run in your family?

405
00:23:33.968 --> 00:23:35.600
<i>Mama!</i>

406
00:23:36.935 --> 00:23:40.373
- Well, there you are!
- Well, it's about time, Idgie.

407
00:23:44.071 --> 00:23:46.646
If you don't look like
the Wild Man Of Borneo.

408
00:23:47.208 --> 00:23:49.170
- There you go.
- Well, thank you.

409
00:23:50.851 --> 00:23:52.005
Guess who's here.

410
00:23:52.044 --> 00:23:53.052
Who?

411
00:23:53.107 --> 00:23:55.693
Ruth. She's staying
with us this summer...

412
00:23:55.718 --> 00:23:59.427
and will be in charge of all the young
people's activities at the church.

413
00:23:59.459 --> 00:24:00.732
Is that why you wanted to see me?

414
00:24:00.757 --> 00:24:03.076
Well, we have so many
nice things planned.

415
00:24:03.138 --> 00:24:04.459
Ruth!

416
00:24:06.443 --> 00:24:08.614
<i>You remember my youngest child?</i>

417
00:24:08.673 --> 00:24:10.263
Of course, I do.

418
00:24:10.412 --> 00:24:12.232
Hi, Idgie.

419
00:24:13.569 --> 00:24:14.966
Hi.

420
00:24:20.643 --> 00:24:22.999
Maybe, this isn't such a good idea.

421
00:24:23.060 --> 00:24:24.768
Oh, it's got to work.

422
00:24:26.252 --> 00:24:28.896
<i>Somebody's got to help her.
I can't.</i>

423
00:24:30.749 --> 00:24:33.372
Are you sure you wanna go
to this here River Club, Miss Ruth?

424
00:24:33.397 --> 00:24:35.119
These ain't no churchgoing folks,
you know?

425
00:24:35.158 --> 00:24:37.910
<i>I'll do just fine, George.
Thank you.</i>

426
00:24:40.143 --> 00:24:41.902
Oh, excuse me.

427
00:24:41.973 --> 00:24:44.668
Is um, Idgie Threadgoode here,
by any chance?

428
00:24:44.706 --> 00:24:46.730
Come on in, honey.
She's right down here.

429
00:24:46.769 --> 00:24:48.621
- Oh, here?
- Uh-huh.

430
00:24:48.652 --> 00:24:49.816
Oh.

431
00:24:51.416 --> 00:24:53.652
I'll see you, Grady Kilgore.

432
00:24:53.691 --> 00:24:56.308
And I'll raise you 20.

433
00:24:56.504 --> 00:24:58.551
You ain't got nothing.

434
00:24:58.621 --> 00:25:01.558
Maybe I do and maybe I don't.

435
00:25:01.730 --> 00:25:05.293
Put your money where
your mouth is, Mr. Sheriff.

436
00:25:10.148 --> 00:25:12.547
Well, look what the cat brung in.

437
00:25:12.873 --> 00:25:15.047
I came to talk to you.

438
00:25:16.947 --> 00:25:19.164
You're gonna have to wait.
I'm busy.

439
00:25:19.310 --> 00:25:20.966
Come on, Grady.
This is your big chance.

440
00:25:20.998 --> 00:25:22.281
You in or out?

441
00:25:22.390 --> 00:25:24.530
It'll make you a rich man.

442
00:25:24.617 --> 00:25:27.140
You're just bluffing again as usual.

443
00:25:27.250 --> 00:25:29.029
I'm afraid you're gonna
have to excuse Idgie.

444
00:25:29.054 --> 00:25:30.211
- She's going home for dinner.
- Hey!

445
00:25:30.236 --> 00:25:31.239
- Nice meeting you.
- Where you going?

446
00:25:31.264 --> 00:25:33.289
- Say goodbye, Idgie.
- Excuse me.

447
00:25:34.105 --> 00:25:36.112
Where the hell are you going
with my money?

448
00:25:36.144 --> 00:25:37.839
We're going home.

449
00:25:38.112 --> 00:25:39.605
Who are you to boss me around?

450
00:25:39.636 --> 00:25:41.379
I'm the one holding your money,
that's who.

451
00:25:41.425 --> 00:25:42.839
Give it back.

452
00:25:43.055 --> 00:25:44.917
Now, get in the car.

453
00:25:47.042 --> 00:25:48.207
All right.

454
00:25:48.253 --> 00:25:49.878
I'll get in the car.

455
00:25:50.258 --> 00:25:51.901
You win.

456
00:25:52.939 --> 00:25:54.550
Come on.

457
00:25:55.809 --> 00:25:57.635
Sucker!

458
00:25:57.940 --> 00:26:00.042
I'll leave here when I want to.

459
00:26:00.096 --> 00:26:03.464
I just don't know how you can break
your mother's heart like you do.

460
00:26:03.589 --> 00:26:05.800
I'm not doing anything to my mother.

461
00:26:05.839 --> 00:26:06.706
- Oh, no?
- No.

462
00:26:06.721 --> 00:26:08.135
Why do you think
I'm over here for the summer?

463
00:26:08.160 --> 00:26:09.518
Your mother was worried about you.

464
00:26:09.566 --> 00:26:12.206
She thought I might be able
to try to talk sense into you.

465
00:26:12.240 --> 00:26:14.458
But you're too busy being selfish.

466
00:26:14.487 --> 00:26:16.388
What are you talking about?

467
00:26:17.341 --> 00:26:20.505
Idgie, you're not the only one
who lost Buddy.

468
00:26:21.160 --> 00:26:22.536
We all...

469
00:26:22.560 --> 00:26:23.842
miss him, but...

470
00:26:23.881 --> 00:26:27.091
turning your back on
your family is not gonna help.

471
00:26:28.602 --> 00:26:30.825
What's he got to do with anything?

472
00:26:31.493 --> 00:26:35.005
It looks like you're the one
with the problem forgetting my brother.

473
00:26:39.459 --> 00:26:41.991
<i>Why, just ten miles away,</i>

474
00:26:42.037 --> 00:26:43.313
<i>down by the river,</i>

475
00:26:43.344 --> 00:26:46.727
<i>there lurks a den of the devil!</i>

476
00:26:46.961 --> 00:26:48.358
<i>Where liquor...</i>

477
00:26:48.412 --> 00:26:49.982
<i>and gambling...</i>

478
00:26:50.039 --> 00:26:52.828
<i>and sin abide!</i>

479
00:26:53.135 --> 00:26:56.799
Snakes and serpents.

480
00:26:56.841 --> 00:26:58.799
<i>Hey, Scroggins!</i>

481
00:26:58.952 --> 00:27:01.575
You're finally preaching
about something you're kin to.

482
00:27:01.631 --> 00:27:02.708
Snakes.

483
00:27:04.554 --> 00:27:06.210
<i>As I said...</i>

484
00:27:06.312 --> 00:27:11.656
snakes and serpents take many disguises.

485
00:27:11.796 --> 00:27:15.265
<i>Let's turn to page 53 in our hymnal.</i>

486
00:27:21.427 --> 00:27:23.083
Yoo-hoo!

487
00:27:23.786 --> 00:27:27.521
Big George thought
I might find you here.

488
00:27:31.563 --> 00:27:33.930
If you give me a chance,

489
00:27:34.055 --> 00:27:36.321
a chance to get to know you,

490
00:27:36.399 --> 00:27:38.719
maybe it'll be fun.

491
00:27:40.346 --> 00:27:41.852
Fun?

492
00:27:43.657 --> 00:27:47.172
Idgie, just spend some time with me.

493
00:27:48.008 --> 00:27:49.188
Please.

494
00:27:49.235 --> 00:27:50.899
Suit yourself.

495
00:27:52.490 --> 00:27:54.186
Are you sure you don't
wanna back out now?

496
00:27:54.256 --> 00:27:56.429
- It's not too late.
- I'm sure.

